Under the Clean Code guidance, this method is not command-query separation. `findUser` looks like a query, but on a cache miss it mutates `usersById`. That is a hidden side effect, so the strict ruling is: reviewer 1 is correct on the rule.

A strong-reason exception does exist, but it stays an exception. The skill guidance is explicit: cache population still mutates, and a `load-and-return` shape is not CQS; it is only tolerable when the ergonomics or performance benefit is strong enough to justify the impurity. Reviewer 2 is only partially right: internal lazy caching can be acceptable, but it is not a harmless non-issue under Clean Code. It should be treated as a deliberate tradeoff, not as compliant-by-default.

Smallest acceptable alternatives:

Strict CQS split:
```ts
class UserDirectory {
  private readonly usersById = new Map<string, User | undefined>();

  constructor(private readonly repository: UserRepository) {}

  loadUser(id: string): void {
    if (!this.usersById.has(id)) {
      this.usersById.set(id, this.repository.findById(id));
    }
  }

  findUser(id: string): User | undefined {
    return this.usersById.get(id);
  }
}
```

Smallest exception-shaped alternative, if you intentionally keep load-and-return:
```ts
class UserDirectory {
  private readonly usersById = new Map<string, User | undefined>();

  constructor(private readonly repository: UserRepository) {}

  getOrLoadUser(id: string): User | undefined {
    if (!this.usersById.has(id)) {
      this.usersById.set(id, this.repository.findById(id));
    }

    return this.usersById.get(id);
  }
}
```

Ruling: if you want Clean Code compliance on command-query and hidden-side-effect grounds, split it. If you keep the lazy cache inside the returning method, the minimum acceptable move is to name it as a command-query hybrid and treat it as a strong-reason exception rather than pretending it is a pure query.
